         </span>\n        </div>\n<!--[if mso]>\n  <center>\n  <table><tr><td width="580">\n<![endif]-->\n<div class="message-content" }</style><![endif]--><div style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;padding-bottom:10px">\n<p class="" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Animal pose estimation</strong> is focused on automatically detecting and analyzing the postures and positions of animals in images or video footage. The goal is to determine the spatial arrangement of body parts, such as the head, limbs, and tail, for one or multiple animals. This technology has a wide array of applications, from studying animal behavior and biomechanics to wildlife conservation and monitoring.</p>\n<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" target="_blank"></a>MULTIMODAL PERCEPTION<br>\n          </td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td style="border-collapse:collapse; mso-line-height-rule:exactly; word-break:break-word; font-weight:normal; font-size:14px; color:rgb(0,\n            0, 0); font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif"><!--Start First Content-->\n<p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"> <br><a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVC5nR32W7lCGcx6lZ3lkW8pWlss4dJMQTW1cw1Lk4PVHYFW3ZyRnb8vCCqlW9gTNX54fqdtlN1TDmBgnPmQtW2_K0-P73d3nsW2CCCTs8WDq8sW8VNv_r5T59L4N7Vz28rvDTswW8TRzp-4tjxNHW7nKs0W56Tg-FW66L7n515BSS_W4nwDRS2cwytLW90Q0ly1sJqZzW8fv2F51TVdrGW5P-1j86wKLTwW5m9bHr8bYF4MN2Hd6W2xnjwjV8-ZJs8xFk0pN8l-CvP20rfyW3xGn2V5d0nxlW93QYfp5NLhckW22pYTK4kx73jW4vm8P68jkjZMW4vG7q47sP04jW3X4CX61WF_6DW1p7ZQs2sGhvjW5zxJKk7T3MBXN353nK8SB2NBW5Wc_6H5RLZ0wW3y9nlf8jNNm1W2r4z3x34f91kW7ZtdFH86BPcpW4YJmP_490kwgN8RwKM4R31b4W17_CQ473M616N6ht8KXH291xW8cjmTC7QWqXmW8cNdL76LXqDCW9dJlBy8W4D00f2lV9hb04" moz-do-not-send="true" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="0" target="_blank"><strong><font-size: 14px="">Frontiers in Perceptual AI: First-person Video and Multimodal Perception</font-size:></strong></a><a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVC5nR32W7lCGcx6lZ3kVW7hw9Z745bP-DN24MTrw2_KXmW7NzmKl1yV1qYW4hwfc95lKb7sW1FZm6y3x8P6HW33MD3h7qh8SfW2pD76F6BbCfqW5k8RsR5m_tT9W1pTrxR9dqMc-W5_TrnR7z7VTMVTL5ms74LwFWW6QN8bT81v1SZW1pGxc-5glcz7W1NztTN482LTFW5M44VK4ghZ1DN2yh99nWHpgqW95Jw-b31q4tYW1K8zmF4Z-PWFW1WX0h98S95d0W5w8gDt61f9gcW5FpcW61v17qzW1hSq131t-wk8N3pFsxy9PQnSW10yfhz7pz-NYW4xdM881hMBPCW1l6CMl1cb1J7W8BDXJx2X-WkfW2mcQ58539P21VZkw2144fnL7W140CZN6pYxCvW6wsbLM6kfspgN6Rmk9bS1fN3W5vlrsB8CPry9W4pTdJg5qYft7W7scysS54NKDYW8SJtjR8bTmm_W4y0N7H8KwkhCW4f2yG57lvtCkN63sDzmL6wsNW1747Ph8h1rhnf5VX2wz04" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="1" target="_blank"><img alt="Kristen Grauman" style="outline:none; text-decoration:none; -ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border:2px solid; width:225px; height:118px" src="https://www.edge-ai-vision.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/EAiVI_20230927_Kristen-Grauman.jpg" moz-do-not-send="true" width="225" vspace="5" hspace="10" height="118" border="0" align="right"></a><br>\n<!-- insert abstract here -->First-person or “egocentric” perception \nrequires understanding the video and multimodal data that streams from \nwearable cameras and other sensors. The egocentric view offers a special\n window into the camera wearer’s attention, goals, and interactions with\n people and objects in the environment, making it an exciting avenue for\n both augmented reality and robot learning. The multimodal nature is \nparticularly compelling, with opportunities to bring together audio, \nlanguage, and vision.</p><p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"><br>Kristen Grauman, Professor at the University of \nTexas at Austin and Research Director at Facebook AI Research, begins \nher 2023 Embedded Vision Summit keynote presentation by introducing \nEgo4D, a massive new open-sourced multimodal egocentric dataset that \ncaptures the daily-life activity of people around the world. The result \nof a multi-year, multi-institution effort, Ego4D pushes the frontiers of\n first-person multimodal perception with a suite of research challenges \nranging from activity anticipation to audio-visual conversation.</p><p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"><br>\nBuilding on this resource, Grauman presents her group’s ideas for \nsearching egocentric videos with natural language queries (“Where did I \nlast see X? Did I leave the garage door open?”), injecting semantics \nfrom text and speech into powerful video representations, and learning \naudio-visual models to understand a camera wearer’s physical environment\n or augment their hearing in busy places. She also touches on \ninteresting performance-oriented challenges raised by having very long \nvideo sequences (hours!) and ideas for learning to scale retrieval and \nencoders.</p>\n<!--End First Content-->\n<!--Start Second Content-->\n<p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"> <br><br><a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVW5nR32W7Y9pgv6lZ3l1M3NTB6v-kF8W7wKmHL5fmMjGW5MltdJ4YVqKTN4xJ4yPm74z5W33SfcK941mwDW2Rp4S_6MKgD0W24k_D943WT1NW6KKT7Y2tXDkkW1Zkc-w5KCNflW3cgcjF4LmmZSW6Y49h26fGyx3W4gkHnb1H82clW1WKyjm8SwBgCW7HT2_f6bNWl_N4nWmf5nR-j4VP-_C475x7SYW21W_RL1h70mJW3wH_lb1D7Pf3W4vw2z31VKDBmF9bJwmckY8WVxZ0bv4DmpdBVJCtJm5pyBM-W5Fgs7g7f9lQ2W2nC_Tq8HWmgnW1B6HkD3DdJSBW2-XknX6RGFJzW17RPyr1CR5GHW5xZzcK3Sx0nNW3dgz0b6YFhLMVtnS8296rsD7N53_Y4L6RT97W87r1395mS9KlW7myDzq41546YVt30CT4WnhkvW2V7r0C5KTQQpW4GF2DV1dgx4PW8xW6D862KfNPW4kCW8t8pJm-RW6V_hxx515NxwW3mwQmw37B3HHW4RQQd6533zPWVPdnNx71kFdTf5PQWHC04" moz-do-not-send="true" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="0" target="_blank"><strong><font-size: 14px="">Making Sense of Sensors: Combining Visual, Laser and Wireless Sensors to Power Occupancy Insights for Smart Workplaces</font-size:></strong></a><a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVW5nR32W7Y9pgv6lZ3mrW3wXyXh3cQkX1W4wSxSp2_6gPPW97F-WD23LrwKW54JgCN3gffl9W95nNGn7Px4M_W7p3yM58wRxkFW1R9mMR8f__WkW1S7f7r2sLZdCVJ2rnd4pp_8CN8vNJxHQSrNJVR_T4B46mqsxN13WH7V8jlntW8001fr5mPH2LW59SjCM5f1vxhW43tV5D73BtCLW7xlK8B996hqvW1JXfbz3S903GW205zCp8-1k1KW18xCD97VxYRBW5RFT135kTWdjW19jcmv6MHyPYW27jRfJ8N6Vf0VNhdRj1vDTYkW802sls94SLv4W5z8hXw694tFMW7-9phc5G0-z7W788BSl1wq-XPVcmmZT42KryqW9hYnkW6BmCzcV2YFQL8qVp2jW8_1-jW83rQRyW7vcFkP16tbKcW4By7854901mjW2XKxn97XM5K8VYV1JR4CPwPjW1fK9t940R6qjL17CN4Y-ZFW6vGYfY5F11zGW6kW3d46cZB76W1MhrBd1X4-_zW4m6F-x26VpvZW6g_sMZ1mG9q9d9ZTHs04" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="1" target="_blank"><img alt="Camio" style="outline:none; text-decoration:none; -ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border:2px solid; width:225px; height:118px" src="https://www.edge-ai-vision.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/EAiVI_20230927_Camio.jpg" moz-do-not-send="true" width="225" vspace="5" hspace="10" height="118" border="0" align="right"></a><br>\n<!-- insert abstract here -->Just as humans rely on multiple senses to \nunderstand our environment, electronic systems are increasingly equipped\n with multiple types of perceptual sensors. Combining and integrating \ndata from heterogeneous sensors (e.g., image, thermal, motion, LiDAR, \nRF) along with other types of data (e.g., card key swipes) can provide \nvaluable insights. But combining data from heterogeneous sensors is \nchallenging. In this presentation, Rakshit Agrawal, Vice President of \nResearch and Development at Camio, shares his company’s experiences \ndeveloping and applying practical techniques that combine heterogeneous \ndata to enable real-world solutions within buildings. For example, \noccupancy insights in work spaces help to optimize use of space, improve\n staff engagement and productivity, enhance energy efficiency and inform\n maintenance scheduling decisions.</p><br>\n<!--End Second Content--></td>\n        </tr>\n        <!--End Featured Content Section 1-->\n        <!--Start Featured Content Section 2--><tr>\n<td style="border-collapse:collapse; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="1" target="_blank"><img alt="Accelerating AI Panel" style="outline:none; text-decoration:none; -ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border:2px solid; width:225px; These distinguished industry \nexperts—Jeff Bier, panel moderator and Founder of the Edge AI and Vision\n Alliance, Dean Kamen, Founder of DEKA Research and Development, Lokwon \nKim, CEO of DEEPX, Jason Lavene, Director of Advanced Development \nEngineering at Keurig Dr Pepper, and Pete Warden, Chief Executive \nOfficer of Useful Sensors—share their insights on what it will take to \nunlock the full potential of this groundbreaking technology, empowering \nit to enhance ease of use, safety, autonomy and numerous other \ncapabilities across a wide range of applications. The panelists delve \ninto the challenges that early adopters of perceptual AI have faced and \nwhy some product developers may still perceive it as too complicated, \nexpensive or unreliable—and what can be done to address these issues. \nAbove all, they chart a path forward for the industry, aiming to “cross \nthe chasm” and make perceptual AI an accessible and indispensable \nfeature of everyday products.</p>\n<!--End First Content--><br>\n<!--Start Second Content-->\n<p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"> <a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVC5nR32W7lCGcx6lZ3pTW1BNXSD6KsLtpW44bdnL1KXKVHW92StzP4HGm4_W30vCsg2wqyXhW22xPfn8tkgXgW2xJYyt6q6m1bW7rJX_x3r86SFV-sZs8179FCFW63H0fk7-FDZjN2jtz0jj1T-6N6sYgCYbrkqZW92k3xq2fvZwNW1LnQLL2f7HrHW21YBLR6jdv6XW1d79MK2-2QbhW71Pg1_3cfxfsW7x_SqH1VDJ5PW3GP09G10nCrMW16Hpbn1hGtJ4W2YDGv_3Fx2p-W6TdL5T24w81KTGXN-74nbpvW83tgCz3Xs5rHW7YR0NF3DfMYLW6r-gvL2P55TfW5vvSML9glhlWW7Z2C0_7QWSMqW8DFntM6GYR7WN4WsWK22Hz7dV4dnJl4YTx3lW5wlBKp6GRL4gW1195lq143f8bN6ldYcB-px6nW2qTzrN7dDMS0W3_tkhW43v2pQN4Bf8qqnP_6BW5njvh16Q-JHdV2Jy7H1Tw06XN21fNkQ4pfjyW8HsGWy7C9m1Jf2Hl6lR04" moz-do-not-send="true" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="0" target="_blank"><strong><font-size: 14px="">Generative AI: How Will It Impact Edge Applications and Machine Perception?</font-size:></strong></a><a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGVC5nR32W7lCGcx6lZ3lcW7hhFJz6HdRTFW2NklKv7Lsc6RW4v83sK2FjsSLW7_bHx614d1mwW4sxw9s527nd5W2zqbQ-1Nd4MdW5xyBwy1xgty9W7YysPK8VSHn7W95ghTH4-t61dW8jZwG-44Cz6VW3BV6D-8fQy7fW13W2TY6S9T3RVbtX7q7611vJW3GNBfM9lGnQxW8GV0VN50QMsHW1DSd0w6fgp-3W5m83gs4f5wmmVrLrcC3fHsWvW5H5P4n8MNN7jW6TJ0XC6FvXQMW3RF9TX5s-yTgW5m9h-t1gFxwJW7WpHTv1VnPDWW61Td7M49QppmW2M1LtQ8DbS8JW3NGn3n1D4wswW2j1_xH17J7zjN3bP-0M-jWcdW8C__2s8r6L-8W4LXQDc1yGn-TW7h3qck1QXh7BW2FkCvR32GmyNW2_XLL26CZ8zjW9kJ1hs4bZNbvW1_Ylbs8Bm-_SW5CLXYK6JgkF0W47KP8B8t8n8-W1Xvt4Q85c2N3W6ggTBD3b8tkrW4Cx9Cg5QJpgRf51PkGv04" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="1" target="_blank"><img alt="Generative AI Panel" style="outline:none; text-decoration:none; -ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border:2px solid; width:225px; height:118px" src="https://www.edge-ai-vision.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/EAiVI_20230927_Generative-AI-Panel.jpg" moz-do-not-send="true" width="225" vspace="5" hspace="10" height="118" border="0" align="right"></a><br>\n<!-- insert abstract here -->Seemingly overnight, ChatGPT has spurred \nmassive interest in—and excitement around—generative AI, and has become \nthe fastest growing application in history. How will generative AI \ntransform how we think about AI, and how we use it? What types of \ncommercial applications are best suited for solutions powered by today’s\n generative AI technology? Will recent advances in generative AI change \nhow we create and use discriminative AI models, like those used for \nmachine perception? Will generative AI obviate the need for massive \nreservoirs of hand-labeled training data? Will it accelerate our ability\n to create systems that effortlessly meld multiple types of data, such \nas text, images and sound? With state-of-the-art generative models \nexceeding 100 billion parameters, will generative models ever be \nsuitable for deployment at the edge? If so, for what use cases? This \nlively and insightful panel discussion explores these and many other \nquestions around the rapidly evolving role of generative AI in edge and \nmachine-perception applications. Panelists include Sally Ward-Foxton, \npanel moderator and Senior Reporter at <i>EE Times</i>, Greg Kostello, CTO and \nCo-Founder of Huma.AI, Vivek Pradeep, Partner Research Manager at \nMicrosoft, Steve Teig, CEO of Perceive, and Roland Memisevic, Senior \nDirector at Qualcomm AI Research.</p><br>\n<!--End Second Content--></td>\n</tr>\n<!--End Featured Content Section 2--><!--Start Upcoming Industry Events-->\n    <tr>\n      <td style="border-collapse:collapse; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="1" target="_blank"><img alt="Qualcomm" style="outline:none; text-decoration:none; -ms-interpolation-mode:bicubic; border:2px solid; width:225px; height:118px" src="https://www.edge-ai-vision.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/EAiVI_20230705_Qualcomm-EAVisPY.jpg" moz-do-not-send="true" width="225" vspace="5" hspace="10" height="118" border="0" align="right"></a><br>\n              <!-- insert abstract here -->Qualcomm’s Cognitive ISP\n              is the <a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGWv3qgyTW95jsWP6lZ3nZW6NdV7p9f1dcBW8mKq7h5Mzd8bW3lP8X93TNXGQW2W89-42Q90T1N4Xt-ChgJgNsW6RRKy47KGzpjW5__Tc43xZBzpW8dXsqR4r4dglW3-h2cf2P8Z9kW6FJ1V54v3ysLW5q9JN-19XKJYW5sHh7c7_gmC2W1-P75g7_FySFW2TtfPc7cq_CYW2xnFsc1hCz7MW4-3zp83LHz_BW2ZVsJ53H-TJhW52h9zV1mBGjPW7StM4g1PnDVtN76GFKCHtRRpW5VCPhk6z-4RtW5msjS-6j9p96W8S9qpw4CBf49W6N3qmL4zB5BnN8Q6TQvYS4M9W8tTKFf90qQVRW8-FKkK35RgGHVzq1Vk3w86ssW2gfnW_7vRbxGW663whX2WSptff57cKTx04" moz-do-not-send="true" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="0" target="_blank">2023 Edge AI and Vision Product\n                of the Year Award</a> winner in the Cameras and Sensors \n             category. The Cognitive ISP (within the Snapdragon 8 Gen 2 \nMobile Platform) is the only ISP for smartphones that can apply the AI \nphoto-editing technique called “Semantic Segmentation” in real-time. \nSemantic Segmentation is like “Photoshop layers,” but handled completely\n within the ISP. It will turn great photos into spectacular photos. \nSince it’s real-time, it’s running while you’re capturing photos and \nvideos – or even before. You can see objects in the viewfinder being \nenhanced as you’re getting ready to shoot. A real-time Segmentation \nFilter is groundbreaking. This means the camera is truly contextually \naware of what it’s seeing. Qualcomm achieved this by building a physical\n bridge between the ISP and the DSP – it’s called “Hexagon Direct Link”.\n The DSP runs Semantic Segmentation neural networks in real-time. Thanks\n to Hexagon Direct Link, the DSP and the ISP can operate simultaneously.\n The ISP captures images and the DSP assigns context to every image in \nreal-time.</p>\n            <p style="mso-line-height-rule:exactly"><br>Please see <a href="https://info.edge-ai-vision.com/e3t/Ctc/UB+113/d2qCg004/VWZZJ03XMLgMW8jXH0s66wfTBW74N_GZ53Y1z6N65wGV05nR32W69t95C6lZ3p5W84W-Pl5z0FZkVRhbVd4l2ZJ_W8zcrcw2P97qBW8KN-6N74nN2CW3XLHYh6ChL9_Vp8p872y8GddW22g2RG4dTlQSW2PKNJ37jSdBtV_NCPc2WRmLjW1m05507bblHvN3ZxjHNQtMJ_W8sFzSL1PRjNTW16SsHc8gqDS1W4NCDtl7qqg0BW6gC-Ff3sRc9DW5VyCqM3PlphYW2XzWRz8pPzTdW1wDYvQ5kx9W2W3fwfnc353VXmW8rWvpF141FCFW2DGcvT5wvMJKW2vmhVn1wvYMxW5C6bLM9j6FzvW2cZ4l71-7Xm3W4l6wrB8zK1D_VDXJMf5QhL_sW9gzDKK50NssRW4Z3DDP2WnQGXW3vxrD34qQklwVt7cly2HMTrTW1n75Qq20JGVBN7XFL-4zvd_WW67Qc-h1XnP6MMyscXztRlPDW1-x60c8Dk6ZlW1j0psQ40svw5f5gVNfq04" moz-do-not-send="true" style="color:#00a4bd; mso-line-height-rule:exactly" data-hs-link-id="2" target="_blank">here</a> for more information on Qualcomm’s Cognitive ISP. Re-order your Workspaces 📚</b><br><br>\n       Your Workspaces just got better and more customisable. <br><br>\n          You can now organise your books in each Workspace to match your course timeline, themes or priorities. <br><br><b>💡Study tip:</b> When compiling resources in your Workspace to use for an assignment, try sorting them from most relevant to least relevant! That way you can go down the list, reading the strongest material first to rely on and pull less information from the resources that aren’t as helpful.</div>\n    \n                </td>\n              </tr>\n            \n              <tr>\n                <td align="left" class="scaled-padding button" style="font-size: 0px; Listen and learn 🎧</b><br><br>\n         Perlego’s Read Aloud feature was trialled earlier this year. Keeping reading and learning impairments that rely on audio support at the forefront of our research, we wanted to make this tool as accessible as possible. <br> <br> To our excitement, feedback has been even better than we hoped with readers listing the following benefits:<br><br><b>\n          \n  \n        \n          \n            <li>Improves focus</li>\n            <li>Deepens comprehension\n\n\n</li>\n            <li>Saves time</li>\n            <li>Allows a break for your eyes</li>\n            <li> Enables notes and highlights to be made while listening along</li>\n          \n        \n          \n <br>\n          🪄 Fun fact: </b>Learners who use this tool are able to read for an average of 33% longer.</div>\n    \n                </td>\n              </tr>\n            \n              <tr>\n                <td align="left" class="scaled-padding button" style="font-size: 0px; style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;color:#333333;max-width:600px;margin:30px auto;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif">\n  <!--[if mso]><style>.button-table { padding: 12px 0 }</style><![endif]--><div style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;padding-bottom:10px">\n<p class="" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em">Hello Samuel Joseph,</p>\n<p class="" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em">This is Satya Mallick from LearnOpenCV.com.</p>\n<p class="" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">TrOCR (transformer-based Optical Character Recognition)</strong> models are some of the best-performing OCR models. Our previous article analyzed how well they perform on single-line printed and handwritten text. However, like any other deep learning model, they have their limitations. TrOCR does not perform well on curved text out of the box. This article will take the TrOCR series a step further by <strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">fine-tuning TrOCR model on a curved text dataset</strong>.</p>\n<p class="" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em">In today\'s article, We will use the Hugging Face Trainer API for training the model. To complete the entire process, the following steps must be followed:</p>\n<ul class="unordered_list" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333;margin-bottom:1em;list-style-position:inside">\n<li class="list_item" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333"><span style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Prepare and analyze the curved text images dataset.</strong></span></li>\n<li class="list_item" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333"><span style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Load the TrOCR Small Printed model from Hugging Face.</strong></span></li>\n<li class="list_item" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333"><span style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Initialize the Hugging Face Sequence to Sequence Trainer API.</strong></span></li>\n<li class="list_item" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333"><span style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Define the evaluation metric</strong></span></li>\n<li class="list_item" style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5em;font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:#333333"><span style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit"><strong style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;color:inherit;font-family:inherit;font-size:inherit">Train the model and run inference.</strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<!--[if !mso]>--><table width="100%" style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"><tbody style="font-family:Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"><tr Don\'t miss the playable, <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/a3i38toqWTs76IjNvhfwlw~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QpaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL3Byb3Bqb2NrZXkvcGVuL2R5d055QlFXA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~">pure CSS Breakout game</a> at the end!</div>\n                                      </div>\n                                    \n                                      <div class="spark-item" data-type="pen">\n                                        <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/QC8JQJAgvk90A09Of7gMdg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QoaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL2Zpbm5odm1hbi9wZW4vYkdPWXBiT1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">\n                                          <img class="spark-thumb" src="https://production-codepen-email-assets.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/production/AVdQX4wlTlp7S5RDthUb_deep-space.png" alt="Deep Space" height="" width="260" />\n                                        </a>\n                                        <div class="spark-item-type">pen</div>\n                                        <div class="spark-title"><a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/QC8JQJAgvk90A09Of7gMdg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QoaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL2Zpbm5odm1hbi9wZW4vYkdPWXBiT1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">Deep Space</a></div>\n                                        <div class="spark-desc">Take a journey into the unknown with Bence Szabo\'s latest #PetitePatterns — this one\'s only 557 bytes! Then check out Bence\'s <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/m4QBgLGSK6qL6xp8U5ZcbQ~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QkaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL2NvbGxlY3Rpb24vRFJNS2RCVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">incredible collection</a> of 90+ more patterns.</div>\n                                      </div>\n                                    \n                                  </mj-raw>\n                                </div>\n                              </td>\n                            </tr>\n                          </tbody>\n                        </table>\n                      </td>\n                    </tr>\n                  </tbody>\n                </table>\n              </div>\n              <!--[if mso | IE]></td></tr></table><![endif]-->\n            </td>\n          </tr>\n        </tbody>\n      </table>\n    </div>\n    <!--[if mso | IE]></td></tr></table><table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="" role="presentation" style="width:600px;" width="600" bgcolor="#131417" ><tr><td style="line-height:0px;font-size:0px;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;"><![endif]-->\n    <div style="background:#131417;background-color:#131417;margin:0px auto;max-width:600px;">\n      <table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="background:#131417;background-color:#131417;width:100%;">\n        <tbody>\n          <tr>\n            <td style="direction:ltr;font-size:0px;padding:20px 0;padding-top:15px;text-align:center;">\n              <!--[if mso | IE]><table role="presentation" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td class="" style="vertical-align:top;width:600px;" ><![endif]-->\n              <div class="mj-column-per-100 mj-outlook-group-fix" style="font-size:0px;text-align:left;direction:ltr;display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:100%;">\n                <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" width="100%">\n                  <tbody>\n                    <tr>\n                      <td style="vertical-align:top;padding:15px;">\n                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="" width="100%">\n                          <tbody>\n                            <tr>\n                              <td align="left" style="font-size:0px;padding:10px 25px;word-break:break-word;">\n                                <div style="font-family:Lato, system-ui, sans-serif;font-size:13px;text-align:left;color:#e3e4e8;">\n                                  <mj-raw>\n                                    <h2 class="news-header" style="margin: 0 0 5px 0;">\n                                      <img src="https://assets.codepen.io/t-1/chriscorner.png" style="width: 65px;" /> Chris’ Corner\n                                    </h2>\n                                    <p style="color: #9dabc9; margin: 0 0 15px 0;font-size: 16px;">A collection of web design and development news and thoughts from CodePen\'s own Chris Coyier.</p>\n                                    <div class="news-bar"></div>\n                                  </mj-raw>\n                                  <mj-raw>\n                                    <div class="news-content">\n                                      <p>CSS animation rules. Just have a look at… CodePen lol.</p>\n\n<p>There was a (long) time when it didn’t exist, though. My old buddy Jonathan Snook <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/KkpV0AzVoauS-er3lkYTcA~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RGaHR0cHM6Ly9zbm9vay5jYS9hcmNoaXZlcy9odG1sX2FuZF9jc3Mvc2hpZnRpbmctb3Bpbmlvbi1jc3MtYW5pbWF0aW9uc1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">wrote in 2007</a> that he didn’t like the idea of animation coming to CSS at all, but had <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/KkpV0AzVoauS-er3lkYTcA~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RGaHR0cHM6Ly9zbm9vay5jYS9hcmNoaXZlcy9odG1sX2FuZF9jc3Mvc2hpZnRpbmctb3Bpbmlvbi1jc3MtYW5pbWF0aW9uc1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">changed his mind by 2009</a>.</p>\n\n<p>They’ve evolved a bit since those early days. They are GPU-accelerated now. We don’t need vendor prefixes on the properties. We can animate more properties, including the values of Custom Properties (especially if we <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/ZbbWyBP0qIlEkckawg8J4A~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0Q6aHR0cHM6Ly9kZXZlbG9wZXIubW96aWxsYS5vcmcvZW4tVVMvZG9jcy9XZWIvQ1NTL0Bwcm9wZXJ0eVcDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">type them</a>). But they haven’t changed <em>that</em> much, and that’s one of the cool things about the web. Actual web platform things don’t change under our feet that dramatically, making them worth learning because that knowledge has a long shelf life.</p>\n\n<p>What also evolves is how people use them, best practices, and the clever tricks that need to be discovered.</p>\n\n<p>Here’s one!</p>\n\n<p>I saw a blog post by Harold Cooper a little while back called Spinning Diagrams with CSS. It’s since been gone’d from the internet, but the ol’ archive caught it and <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/PjxjLkCsYL9HwDVm9ar_cw~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QqaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL2NocmlzY295aWVyL3Blbi9iR09ZWVdlVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">I’ve made a Pen out of it</a>, too, for posterity. Harold was showing off mathematical formulas that benefitted from a 3D look, like this:</p>\n\n<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/css-tricks/image/upload/c_scale,w_458,h_126,dpr_2/f_auto,q_auto/v1695240855/CleanShot-2023-09-20-at-13.13.24.gif?_i=AA" alt="animation of a mathematical formula rotating in 3D" width="550"/>\n<p>I <em>completely wimped out</em> there and used an animated GIF. But Harold did not:</p>\n\n<blockquote><p>Several people expressed surprise that the spinning diagrams don’t use any JavaScript or animated image formats, just HTML and CSS.</p></blockquote>\n<p>One of the cool parts of Harold’s tricky is using one animation to spin things, and another animation to <em>un</em>spin them. Notice how the numbers at letters appear to move in 3D space, but always “face forward”. Nobody was thinking about that in 2007, I’ll tell ya that.</p>\n<p>I remember I first read this post over RSS <em>and the animations worked even in RSS</em>. Probably because the styling was built in &lt;style&gt; blocks that my reader respected. So cool.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>Josh Collinsworth wrote <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/prgOAPYrqZA-HfdmNStejQ~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QzaHR0cHM6Ly9qb3NoY29sbGluc3dvcnRoLmNvbS9ibG9nL2dyZWF0LXRyYW5zaXRpb25zVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">Ten tips for better CSS transitions and animations</a> which is full of good practical stuff. Huge fan of #1: “Make them shorter than you think they should be”. I don’t think I’ve ever picked a <code>transition-duration</code> that didn’t get lower and lower over the time I played with it, and even after deploying.</p>\n<p>So many great examples and real-world advice!</p>\n<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/css-tricks/image/upload/c_scale,w_303,h_344,dpr_2/f_auto,q_auto/v1695241250/CleanShot-2023-09-20-at-13.19.49.gif?_i=AA" alt="The phrase \'Play with more delay\' animated with different delay times" width="350"/>\n<p>Some of the advice, like “don’t use browser defaults”, means then having to replace easing with more bespoke stuff ala <code>cublic-bezier</code> curves. Josh has <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/DXiytU64gI_lKidtAfmS7w~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QvaHR0cHM6Ly9qb3NoY29sbGluc3dvcnRoLmNvbS9ibG9nL2Vhc2luZy1jdXJ2ZXNXA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~">a more in-depth post</a> on that as well that is very helpful. I probably rely on browser defaults too much when it comes to this stuff, but sometimes when I play with custom curves they end up feeling worse to me. Maybe I shouldn’t just take the first thing Copilot gives me 😬 and actually understand it.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>If you haven’t heard of <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/MkfCTzLXPaf8EhtcOfTKww~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QzaHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQWZ0ZXJfRGFya18oc29mdHdhcmUpVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">After Dark</a>, you’ve probably heard of Flying Toasters. It’s this iconic screensaver from the 1990s where, uh, flying toasters fly in sort-of 3D-looking space across your screen. From the top right to the bottom left, actually.</p>\n<p>Good news, Bryan Braun <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/W7YaQot9xeQfjqPW2qDrVw~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RCaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnJ5YW5icmF1bi5jb20vYWZ0ZXItZGFyay1jc3MvYWxsL2ZseWluZy10b2FzdGVycy5odG1sVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">did it in CSS</a>, along with <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/6spehvgxfE9gycbl8KOndA~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QqaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnJ5YW5icmF1bi5jb20vYWZ0ZXItZGFyay1jc3MvVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">all the other After Dark screensavers</a>.</p>\n<img src="https://res.cloudinary.com/css-tricks/image/upload/c_scale,w_848,h_585,dpr_2/f_auto,q_auto/v1695332250/Screenshot-2023-09-21-at-2.37.09-PM.png?_i=AA" alt="The \'flying toasters\' screensaver, with winged toasters and slices of toasted bread scattered on the screen. " width="550"/>\n<p>…annnnnd he did that in 2014 which shows you how on top of things I am. (I like clicking on the <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/hlEmj32qBNmq7KKRsq-UYg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RAaHR0cHM6Ly9naXRodWIuY29tL2JyeWFuYnJhdW4vYWZ0ZXItZGFyay1jc3MvZ3JhcGhzL2NvbnRyaWJ1dG9yc1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">Contributors</a> page of a repo as it clearly shows you the year of the first commit.) You can kinda get a feel of the vintage by seeing chunks of CSS like this:</p>\n<pre><code>\n      -webkit-animation: fly 10s linear infinite;\n         -moz-animation: fly 10s linear infinite;\n          -ms-animation: fly 10s linear infinite;\n           -o-animation: fly 10s linear infinite;\n              animation: fly 10s linear infinite;\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</code></pre>\n<p>That’s just how we used to roll.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>VERY NEW THING ALERT. I need to do a deeper dive on this but I think it’s worth mentioning here right now. I’m assuming you know what <code>cubic-bezier()</code> is, partially because I literally linked to an article about it from Josh above.</p>\n<p>Cubic bezier has four parameters. No more. No less.</p>\n<p>The new thing here is <code>linear()</code> which functions as an alternative for animation timing values, which can take any number of values. <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/MlnJ9mDiDztbXnwU4iQBig~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QmaHR0cHM6Ly9mdWxseXN0YWNrZWQubmV0L3Bvc3RzL2xpbmVhci9XA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~">Ollie Williams has a great article on it</a>, and I’ll take a quote that he took because it’s a nice quick summary:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>MDN <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/hyX2J6STqUk6sZNNYQyPpQ~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RXaHR0cHM6Ly9kZXZlbG9wZXIubW96aWxsYS5vcmcvZW4tVVMvZG9jcy9XZWIvQ1NTL2Vhc2luZy1mdW5jdGlvbiNsaW5lYXJfZWFzaW5nX2Z1bmN0aW9uVwNzcGNCCmT6u8gRZQZrtM1SHDIwMTUwMTUwMkByYWphbGFrc2htaS5lZHUuaW5YBAAAAAA~">explains the syntax</a>: <code>linear(0, 0.25 75%, 1)</code> produces a linear easing function that spends 75% of the time transitioning from <code>0</code> to <code>.25</code> and the last 25% transitioning from <code>.25</code> to <code>1</code>.”</p>\n<pre><code>&lt;p&gt;A more real-world example looks like this:&lt;/p&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<pre><code>animation-timing-function: linear(0, 0.218 2.1%, 0.862 6.5%, 1.114, 1.296 10.7%, 1.346, 1.37 12.9%, 1.373, 1.364 14.5%, 1.315 16.2%, 1.032 21.8%, 0.941 24%, 0.891 25.9%, 0.877, 0.869 27.8%, 0.87, 0.882 30.7%, 0.907 32.4%, 0.981 36.4%, 1.012 38.3%, 1.036,1.046 42.7% 44.1%, 1.042 45.7%, 0.996 53.3%, 0.988, 0.984 57.5%, 0.985 60.7%,1.001 68.1%, 1.006 72.2%, 0.998 86.7%, 1);</code></pre>\n<p>Fancy! There is a 92% chance this will be generated by a tool for you, like maybe <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/eQ9XvboyJkueUO0xbMtwGw~~/AABEfgA~-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">this one</a>, and others likely to spring up. Get it? Spring?</p>\n\t</blockquote>\n<p>All those points, well, there is a straight line between them, which I guess is why “linear” is the name. But it’s kind of a sucky name because it makes you think it’s going to behave like the”linear” keyword which is boring and straight all the way through. Oh well.</p>\n<p>You should probably read <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/htmgBBLw_3Zq8qQ_gO3gcA~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RBaHR0cHM6Ly9kZXZlbG9wZXIuY2hyb21lLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jc3MtbGluZWFyLWVhc2luZy1mdW5jdGlvbi9XA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~">Create complex animation curves in CSS with the linear() easing function</a> by Bramus. Ben Holmes made <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/GnV7WXCk8jKQqqbmvQzVRw~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0Q1aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL2Job2xtZXNkZXYtdGhlLXJlYWN0b3IvcGVuL3h4UUJ2cVJXA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~">a very clicky button</a> I’ll make you click over to click.</p>\n<p>Adam Argyle’s <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/j8JJFUgsnbtsHrxs4d9zxg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0Q6aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9DaHJvbWl1bURldi9zdGF0dXMvMTcwMzg0NjMzMzM2NTI4NTM2OVcDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">one-minute explanation</a> will probably do you right, as well.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>Remember when CSS nesting was coming of age and browser vendors were putting out all those polls to get you to vote on the syntax? I thought that was kinda cool, even though every single person was just like “can it be like Sass?” and they are like “no” and then they made it just like Sass.</p>\n<p>But anyway!</p>\n<p>I thought that’s what they were doing with <code>animation-composition</code> in Bramus’ <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/uspm665aZPvmK_kHl4eFKg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0RAaHR0cHM6Ly9kZXZlbG9wZXIuY2hyb21lLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jc3MtYW5pbWF0aW9uLWNvbXBvc2l0aW9uL1cDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">Specify how multiple animation effects should composite with animation-composition</a>, but it turns out he’s just showing us how to use it.</p>\n<p>It’s a little in the weeds really, but it really is something that comes up sometimes with animation. It helps with when multiple animations affect the same property. The <code>transform</code> property is notorious for making this complicated because one <code>transform</code> might be rotating an element, while another is <code>translate</code> moving it, but they would overwrite each other in the past, so you’d have to nest elements or something. Now you can <code>replace</code>, <code>add</code>, or <code>accumulate</code> the values, which is really pretty cool.</p>\n\n<p>My first test was this thinking it would work:</p>\n\n<pre><code>button {\n  position: relative;\n  animation-composition: accumulate;\n\n  &:hover {\n    translate: 0 1px;\n  }\n  &:active {\n    translate: 0 1px;\n  }\n}</code></pre>\n\n<p>But nope, I guess pseudo-states like that totally replace the other, so a button isn’t like hovered and active at the same time? I dunno. Honestly, it’s more useful with keyframes than transitions anyway.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p>OK, last thing I promise. Excellent video: <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/BamSLvOdciZvNoB3BIYgYg~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QraHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1CMUo2T3U0cTh2RVcDc3BjQgpk-rvIEWUGa7TNUhwyMDE1MDE1MDJAcmFqYWxha3NobWkuZWR1LmluWAQAAAAA">Animation vs. Math</a>.</p>\n                                      \n                                    </div>\n                                  </mj-raw>\n                                </div>\n                              </td>\n                            </tr>\n                          </tbody>\n                        </table>\n                      </td>\n                    </tr>\n                  </tbody>\n                </table>\n              </div>\n              <!--[if mso | IE]></td></tr></table><![endif]-->\n            </td>\n          </tr>\n        </tbody>\n      </table>\n ><tr><td style="line-height:0px;font-size:0px;mso-line-height-rule:exactly;"><![endif]-->\n    <div style="background:#333845;background-color:#333845;margin:0px auto;max-width:600px;">\n      <table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="background:#333845;background-color:#333845;width:100%;">\n        <tbody>\n          <tr>\n            <td style="direction:ltr;font-size:0px;padding:20px 0;text-align:center;">\n              <!--[if mso | IE]><table role="presentation" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td class="" style="vertical-align:top;width:600px;" ><![endif]-->\n              <div class="mj-column-per-100 mj-outlook-group-fix" style="font-size:0px;text-align:left;direction:ltr;display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:100%;">\n                <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" width="100%">\n                  <tbody>\n                    <tr>\n                      <td style="vertical-align:top;padding:15px;">\n                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" role="presentation" style="" width="100%">\n                          <tbody>\n                            <tr>\n                              <td align="left" style="font-size:0px;padding:10px 25px;word-break:break-word;">\n                                <div style="font-family:Lato, system-ui, sans-serif;font-size:13px;line-height:1;text-align:left;color:#e3e4e8;">\n                                  <mj-raw>\n                                    <h2 class="pro-header">\n                                      <a href="http://post.spmailtechnolo.com/f/a/jdDVg_uyOoz97cnO8bek5g~~/AABEfgA~/RgRm9E20P0QXaHR0cHM6Ly9jb2RlcGVuLmlvL3Byby9XA3NwY0IKZPq7yBFlBmu0zVIcMjAxNTAxNTAyQHJhamFsYWtzaG1pLmVkdS5pblgEAAAAAA~~"> CodePen PRO </a>\n                                    </h2>\n                                    <div class="pro-bar"></div>\n                                    <div class="pro-content">\n                                      <p>Just tuck this into the ol\' brain bank: <a hosted assets, a PRO feature</a>, serve those assets with full CORS permissions. Unlike conventional assembly systems that operate in controlled environments, our project focuses on enabling the robot to navigate and perform assembly tasks in cluttered and dynamic surroundings. By integrating computer vision algorithms, the robot gains the ability to identify and locate assembly components amidst clutter, obstacles, and variations in object positions. Additionally, the force sensor in the robot&#39;s end effector allows for adaptive pressure application, ensuring precise and reliable assembly even with variations in component shapes and sizes. The development of an intelligent assembling system can revolutionize industrial automation, allowing robots to efficiently handle assembly tasks in real-world settings, where objects may be scattered,  overlapping, or randomly placed. 9px;mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;word-break: break-word;color: #757575;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 16px;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;" width="563">\n            <span style="font-size:14px">The architecture of Snowflake is a mix of classic shared-disk and shared-nothing database designs. Snowflake employs a central data repository for persistent data, like shared-disk architectures, available from all compute nodes in the platform. Snowflake executes queries utilizing MPP (massively parallel processing) compute clusters, wherein each node in the cluster stores a part of the whole data set locally, like shared-nothing architectures. This method combines the simplicity of a shared-disk design with the speed and scale-out advantages of a shared-nothing architecture.&nbsp;<a href="https://projectpro.us4.list-manage.com/track/click?u=89cb5799270e8bbf2a9b00d74&id=55c2003bb6&e=0738227199" target="_blank" style="mso-line-height-rule: exactly;-ms-text-size-adjust: href="http://url3090.unity3d.com/ls/click?upn=vEX9nigFznyBvc0R-2FJA8pJRAj-2BE0n6m2ezSghJ9Xxwc4bODT27GalOHcNg5ew3nUuquw49ghGMbJmF-2FG957pHA-3D-3DSqjl_j-2F5VEiPum6wlBAZqcnkL4PzjJ6VJyga0QGYAErcIKmQyE0yLhxdeEho8R6GABUEyUqZHS9zPiuxMpTrj2NDz5rNkAFTk4M9nYSlrZ95U1mAgQpAyOshmGBlt5ZIpMgaynqlT-2FRw4Fh9eZ9WVvOc3TmAncnAXVaqz69lCH4lwX4BSmlThVAJBHteLwqBkMmbH8AHHtnkVKdhw4tW2D-2Fvr3s6Y-2FqTssGLXpgBisiQWRpNcSkCRJakuq3kuXGsgka-2F575jvpR2P3EJHjAqseGkbyqPLLruSWbZvG4AvkQtth-2BiURdyCcSKeQtlXWQ9cnSvNAoKuep66aK-2B-2BQMVgL5-2FPqKnzc11u7ulr6jWOwg-2BUtrCtAQBcTMnbqawBNtfbqXQMHvV2OGPMUhaWwe3lDp-2FV-2FL-2F7nMWMKH2TaOHeXJMuLxKndIiib6u8UgT2-2Fel6CoVJwUUjcY0ebyC0-2FJJ4fSG-2F7g8qycDwH-2FD5Xgr5ZT0KmZHa0Zb5fKRXXjPmTcYyfR24dW136F4vyaDfAOK6r7QpF4HD-2BPorsUFhzojVDqWRHqFHnrcu4-2BtXPTwJNTTOat2Lw0odfHileAoTIJNSOTgNAQY6S85NDkViHhbtRXwo5yaHLEWks6dOdQH0L0xSP3B-2BYpur7qasxogtksY9UPV-2B2k0CGYPIU9p-2FAXoYEusB3H-2FA5SrUTLpRBCu1Pjl2wpybn6VlYFPqZ87-2B-2Fe9SchqYlv8jJeVOkc0xbRqfHOghs0QeH1sGqTzF4Ub-2Fso9NvHZIlIQFDMHzgqgOCdddBE2equS3PitGOfo7PPgzrpbcJprFoacLnk0BuP59oxHbTxChASZh1XCUfwNsUgXHq5WQyg0F5IOPTyUBGtF-2BnxOKVSxmGR0DpNwA9OaL8CHctYcXzkZ1vewsO7nfT8PuzN2zgVqaB5NLdnRLepqdxiEuCPN9A0QG7hMQVBCbHG5o1xBUGhI4m2k4-2F9f77J23cJbrO43q7x7P1dPauoPRZAom76nsbUikAOc8ounAgGYLDgTcE32P-2FuL6-2BrUzxp4WDlB0gsI9plTSaW5PPML414PN-2FESt9-2B7-2FiwzBmrRzehJm8JGj" style="color: #2196f3; text-decoration: none;">open letter on our blog</a> about the changes we’re making to the Unity Runtime Fee pricing policy that we announced last week. These changes were made based on feedback from our community, and we want to ensure you’re aware. We also invite you to read the <a href="http://url3090.unity3d.com/ls/click?upn=vEX9nigFznyBvc0R-2FJA8pMddUo9hcDxptZVjKjzyVNhj3WivkjaxFCU63WOIglS-2FdNdt_j-2F5VEiPum6wlBAZqcnkL4PzjJ6VJyga0QGYAErcIKmQyE0yLhxdeEho8R6GABUEyUqZHS9zPiuxMpTrj2NDz5rNkAFTk4M9nYSlrZ95U1mAgQpAyOshmGBlt5ZIpMgaynqlT-2FRw4Fh9eZ9WVvOc3TmAncnAXVaqz69lCH4lwX4BSmlThVAJBHteLwqBkMmbH8AHHtnkVKdhw4tW2D-2Fvr3s6Y-2FqTssGLXpgBisiQWRpNcSkCRJakuq3kuXGsgka-2F575jvpR2P3EJHjAqseGkbyqPLLruSWbZvG4AvkQtth-2BiURdyCcSKeQtlXWQ9cnSvNAoKuep66aK-2B-2BQMVgL5-2FPqKnzc11u7ulr6jWOwg-2BUtrCtAQBcTMnbqawBNtfbqXQMHvV2OGPMUhaWwe3lDp-2FV-2FL-2F7nMWMKH2TaOHeXJMuLxKndIiib6u8UgT2-2Fel6CoVJwUUjcY0ebyC0-2FJJ4fSG-2F7g8qycDwH-2FD5Xgr5ZT0KmZHa0Zb5fKRXXjPmTcYyfR24dW136F4vyaDfAOK6r7QpF4HD-2BPorsUFhzojVDqWRHqFHnrcu4-2BtXPTwJNTTOat2Lw0odfHileAoTIJNSOTgNAQY6S85NDkViHhbtRXwo5yaHLEWks6dOdQH0L0xSP3B-2BYpur7qasxogtksY9UPV-2B2k0CGYPIU9p-2FAXoYEusB3H-2FA5SrUTLpRBCu1Pjl2wpybn6VlYFPqZ87-2B-2Fe9SchqYlv8jJeVOkc0xbRqfHOghs0QeH1sGqTzF4Ub-2Fso9NvHZIlIQFDMHzgqgOCdddBE2equS3PitGOfo7PPgzrpbcJprFoacLnk0BuP59oxHbTxChASZh1XCUfwNsUgXHq5WQyg0F5IOPTyUBGtF-2BnxOKVSxmGR0DpNwA9OaL8CHctYcXXuN0TQ41nVUE0LFItdAVk2Y4ScOT-2F8F3Pc8zs5E-2F4rHiMBw-2FOD-2B9XzxveOjwu8sS3aPtdxWvoZZG94HDFS7TVrewkaD0-2BOwSDQmEFn-2BmI17Ye-2FBPw2Z5CH1VbHs-2BWuDZ65EYkBI6iPS2qAlxgurEyHDCKezLj5AwCc7mC2FSaY-2Fy7FKkmaZYByMWZzIBWqXi" style="color: #2196f3; text-decoration: none;">FAQ</a> for more details.\n                      <div style="line-height: 16px; height: 16px;">&nbsp;</div>\n                      \nAt a high level, this is what we’re changing:\n                \n<ul>\n  <li><strong style="font-weight: bold;">Unity Personal: No Runtime Fee, splash screen optional.</strong> The Unity Personal plan will remain free and there will be no Runtime Fees for games built with the plan. We will be increasing the revenue limit from $100,000 USD to $200,000 USD and we will remove the requirement to use the <i>Made with Unity</i> splash screen (starting with the LTS version releasing in 2024, currently referred to as the 2023 LTS, or later).\n</li>\n  <li><strong style="font-weight: bold;">Runtime Fee is forward-looking.</strong> For Unity Pro & Enterprise, the Runtime Fee does not apply to any games created with any currently supported Unity versions. It only applies to games created with or upgraded to the LTS version releasing in 2024 (currently referred to as the 2023 LTS) or later.</li>\n                   \n                        <li><strong style="font-weight: bold;">Editor Terms.</strong> We will make sure that you can stay on the terms applicable for the version of Unity you are using  - as long as you keep using that version.\n</li>\n                        <li><strong style="font-weight: bold;">Runtime Fee, self-reported.</strong> On a monthly basis, you have a choice of the lesser of 2.5% revenue share or the calculated amount based on unique initial engagements. Both are self-reported from data you already have available. You will always be billed the lesser amount.</li>\n                      </ul>\n\n                      \n\n                        <div style="line-height: 16px; height: 16px;">&nbsp;</div>\n                      \nWe understand that you may still have questions after reading our letter and the <a href="http://url3090.unity3d.com/ls/click?upn=vEX9nigFznyBvc0R-2FJA8pMddUo9hcDxptZVjKjzyVNhj3WivkjaxFCU63WOIglS-2FjF2u_j-2F5VEiPum6wlBAZqcnkL4PzjJ6VJyga0QGYAErcIKmQyE0yLhxdeEho8R6GABUEyUqZHS9zPiuxMpTrj2NDz5rNkAFTk4M9nYSlrZ95U1mAgQpAyOshmGBlt5ZIpMgaynqlT-2FRw4Fh9eZ9WVvOc3TmAncnAXVaqz69lCH4lwX4BSmlThVAJBHteLwqBkMmbH8AHHtnkVKdhw4tW2D-2Fvr3s6Y-2FqTssGLXpgBisiQWRpNcSkCRJakuq3kuXGsgka-2F575jvpR2P3EJHjAqseGkbyqPLLruSWbZvG4AvkQtth-2BiURdyCcSKeQtlXWQ9cnSvNAoKuep66aK-2B-2BQMVgL5-2FPqKnzc11u7ulr6jWOwg-2BUtrCtAQBcTMnbqawBNtfbqXQMHvV2OGPMUhaWwe3lDp-2FV-2FL-2F7nMWMKH2TaOHeXJMuLxKndIiib6u8UgT2-2Fel6CoVJwUUjcY0ebyC0-2FJJ4fSG-2F7g8qycDwH-2FD5Xgr5ZT0KmZHa0Zb5fKRXXjPmTcYyfR24dW136F4vyaDfAOK6r7QpF4HD-2BPorsUFhzojVDqWRHqFHnrcu4-2BtXPTwJNTTOat2Lw0odfHileAoTIJNSOTgNAQY6S85NDkViHhbtRXwo5yaHLEWks6dOdQH0L0xSP3B-2BYpur7qasxogtksY9UPV-2B2k0CGYPIU9p-2FAXoYEusB3H-2FA5SrUTLpRBCu1Pjl2wpybn6VlYFPqZ87-2B-2Fe9SchqYlv8jJeVOkc0xbRqfHOghs0QeH1sGqTzF4Ub-2Fso9NvHZIlIQFDMHzgqgOCdddBE2equS3PitGOfo7PPgzrpbcJprFoacLnk0BuP59oxHbTxChASZh1XCUfwNsUgXHq5WQyg0F5IOPTyUBGtF-2BnxOKVSxmGR0DpNwA9OaL8CHctYcXsfz-2FthVD0TN0OB1Nzpl5-2FMs4jByBYT1mQCfSn9FYt3Tw-2FZ7Vm-2FYNIcgbvPG7Jr4WWSeEVYCh3NyZbBNGjXbFlGx-2Fh-2FMVFp0aNnUYL-2Fe016x832QEN1keJIAoM6U1HIpjkl2CmiAOVaRspyl8S7hw11rv-2FL-2FFHShAMOqU5h7wQJhxCQnFiphDWiVLSSCDcIrF" style="color: #2196f3; text-decoration: none;">FAQ</a>.
